(Alexander Joe, AFP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg - Supporters of legal rhino horn trade in South Africa say the country's top court has ruled in their favour, rejecting a government appeal to preserve a 2009 ban on the domestic trade.Rhino breeder John Hume said on Wednesday that the Constitutional Court rejected the appeal late last month.Rhinos are heavily poached. Rhino breeders believe poaching would be undercut by a regulated trade, while critics say trade will spur poaching.OSCAP is a group that opposes trade in rhino horns. It says the ruling means domestic trade is legal, but notes that regulations are still being drafted and could be subject to a legal challenge.Most of the world's rhinos live in South Africa.An international ban on trade in rhino horns has been in place since 1977.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.